🧠 Core Understanding
🔹 What is a beautiful sequence?

A sequence is beautiful if:

It is a regular bracket sequence (RBS)
OR
Its reverse is RBS
🔹 What is RBS?

Classic:

Balanced brackets
Prefix never negative
Total sum = 0
💡 Key Observation (MOST IMPORTANT)

👉 If total ( ≠ total ) → IMPOSSIBLE

Because:

Even after coloring, each color must form a valid sequence
Total imbalance cannot be fixed
🔥 MAIN IDEA

We want to split the string into minimum colors such that:

Each color subsequence is:

either valid RBS
or reverse RBS
🧠 Insight That Cracks Problem
Case 1: String itself is RBS

👉 Answer = 1 color

Case 2: Reverse string is RBS

👉 Answer = 1 color

Case 3: Otherwise

👉 Answer = 2 colors

⚡ WHY 2 COLORS ALWAYS WORK?

We use prefix balance idea:

Traverse string
Maintain cnt (balance)
(  → +1  
)  → -1
💥 Key Trick
When prefix becomes negative → invalid forward
That part can be valid in reverse

👉 So:

Positive prefix → color 1
Negative prefix → color 2
🔁 Visualization

Example:

s = ))()((

Balance:

i:   0 1 2 3 4 5
s:   ) ) ( ) ( (
cnt: -1 -2 -1 -2 -1 0

👉 Always negative → reverse is valid
👉 So 1 color enough

⚠️ Important Subtlety

Your logic:

if(cnt < 0) neg = true;
if(cnt > 0) neg = false;

👉 This is tracking current segment type

🧩 Why your approach works
You dynamically decide:
current prefix behaving like forward RBS → color 1
broken prefix → assign color 2

👉 This ensures:

color 1 → forward valid
color 2 → reverse valid
🚨 Edge Case
if(st.size() == 1 && ans[0] == 2)

👉 Means:

everything assigned color 2
i.e. full sequence works in reverse

👉 So convert to 1 color

📌 Final Algorithm
Step 1:

Check total balance
→ if not 0 → -1

Step 2:

Traverse and assign:

Maintain cnt
If prefix valid → color 1
If prefix invalid → color 2
Step 3:

If only one color used:

return 1

Else:

return 2
🧾 Clean Code Version (Refined)
void solve() {
    int n;
    cin >> n;
    string s;
    cin >> s;

    int cnt = 0;
    vector<int> ans(n);
    bool neg = false;

    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if(s[i] == '(') cnt++;
        else cnt--;

        if(cnt < 0) neg = true;
        if(cnt > 0) neg = false;

        ans[i] = neg ? 2 : 1;
    }

    // total balance check
    if(cnt != 0) {
        cout << -1 << endl;
        return;
    }

    // count colors
    set<int> st(ans.begin(), ans.end());

    // if all are color 2 → make them 1
    if(st.size() == 1 && ans[0] == 2) {
        for(auto &x : ans) x = 1;
    }

    cout << st.size() << endl;
    for(auto x : ans) cout << x << " ";
    cout << endl;
}
🧠 Deep Intuition (VERY IMPORTANT)

This problem is NOT about brackets.

It’s about:

Splitting into monotonic prefix segments

Where:

One group never dips below 0 → forward valid
Other group never rises above 0 → reverse valid
